the team in good shape,

72
00:03:02,007 --> 00:03:03,661
and we're pretty far from that.

73
00:03:05,750 --> 00:03:07,448
You've got this.

74
00:03:09,363 --> 00:03:11,234
Babe, I--I gotta go.

75
00:03:11,278 --> 00:03:13,845
- Love you.

76
00:03:14,890 --> 00:03:16,761
- Don't look so worried, Paz.

77
00:03:16,805 --> 00:03:18,285
You're just here
for your routine scan

78
00:03:18,328 --> 00:03:21,201
to check on the progress
of your tumor.

79
00:03:21,244 --> 00:03:22,376
Did your sister tell you

80
00:03:22,419 --> 00:03:23,855
how promising
her last PET scan was?

81
00:03:23,899 --> 00:03:26,902
- That's not why she's upset.

82
00:03:26,945 --> 00:03:29,861
Sorry, but you should tell her.
- Paz?

83
00:03:29,905 --> 00:03:32,777
- As you know...

84
00:03:32,821 --> 00:03:36,216
when uterine cancer
threw a wrench

85
00:03:36,259 --> 00:03:38,609
into my IVF plan, I mean,

86
00:03:38,653 --> 00:03:41,482
Jasmine stepped up
to be my surrogate.

87
00:03:41,525 --> 00:03:44,702
And she did months of testing
and hormone injections...

88
00:03:44,746 --> 00:03:46,661
- I was going to be implanted
next week.

89
00:03:46,704 --> 00:03:49,272
- But our insurance company
suddenly changed the rule.

90
00:03:49,316 --> 00:03:51,492
Now they won't cover surrogacy
of any kind.

91
00:03:51,535 --> 00:03:54,364
- That's insane.
When did they change the rules?

92
00:03:54,408 --> 00:03:55,844
Three weeks ago, Max.

93
00:03:55,887 --> 00:03:58,368
They basically stopped
covering surrogacy overnight.

94
00:03:58,412 --> 00:04:00,370
- Even though both sisters
are with the same company.

95
00:04:00,414 --> 00:04:02,329
- Barcroft,
who will cover Jasmine

96
00:04:02,372 --> 00:04:03,373
if she wants to have a baby

97
00:04:03,417 --> 00:04:05,070
and Paz if she could
have a baby,

98
00:04:05,114 --> 00:04:06,768
but they won't cover Jasmine if
she wants to have Paz's baby.

99
00:04:06,811 --> 00:04:09,553
I mean, it's not as if Paz's
embryo inside Jasmine's womb

100
00:04:09,597 --> 00:04:11,076
is gonna cost them
any more money.

101
00:04:11,120 --> 00:04:13,383
- Right, but having no baby
saves them a lot of money.

102
00:04:13,427 --> 00:04:15,298
- Adoption agencies
aren't exactly queuing up

103
00:04:15,342 --> 00:04:18,345
to give kids to women
with cancer, so what now?

104
00:04:18,388 --> 00:04:19,998
I mean, Paz waits three years

105
00:04:20,042 --> 00:04:21,739
to see if her uterus
is still "hospitable"

106
00:04:21,783 --> 00:04:23,001
after all the radiation?

107
00:04:23,045 --> 00:04:24,742
That's her only shot
of becoming a mother?

108
00:04:24,786 --> 00:04:27,919
- Helen, if Barcroft
changed the rule overnight,

109
00:04:27,963 --> 00:04:31,401
then let's get them
to change it right back.

110
00:04:34,361 --> 00:04:35,579
- Dr. Ligon isn't back yet?

111
00:04:35,623 --> 00:04:37,668
- Not only is he
still on vacation,

112
00:04:37,712 --> 00:04:39,627
he is also the kind of person
who turns his phone off

113
00:04:39,670 --> 00:04:41,193
while on vacation.

114
00:04:41,237 --> 00:04:42,804
Who does that to an addict?
- Use someone else already.

115
00:04:42,847 --> 00:04:44,719
I heard great things
about Dr. Parsons.

116
00:04:45,981 --> 00:04:47,939
- Seven-year-old
accidental choking victim.

117
00:04:47,983 --> 00:04:49,376
Got caught in window blinds.

118
00:04:49,419 --> 00:04:51,682
Heart rate 118.
BP 110 over 78.

119
00:04:51,726 --> 00:04:54,859
18 respirations per minute.
Setting 98% on nasal cannula.

120
00:04:54,903 --> 00:04:56,034
- Okay, let's get him
to trauma one.

121
00:04:56,078 --> 00:04:59,603
We're gonna take
good care of you, okay?

122
00:04:59,647 --> 00:05:00,909
- That's our son.
- Yeah, you can see him

123
00:05:00,952 --> 00:05:02,432
once the doctors get him
stabilized, okay?

124
00:05:02,476 --> 00:05:04,086
But let me show you
where the waiting room...

125
00:05:04,129 --> 00:05:05,609
- It's gonna be okay.

126
00:05:05,653 --> 00:05:07,742
- Hey, hey, come with me.

127
00:05:10,614 --> 00:05:11,876
- Sweetie, come on.

128
00:05:17,012 --> 00:05:18,709
- Look straight ahead.

129
00:05:18,753 --> 00:05:20,581
That's it, Calvin.

130
00:05:20,624 --> 00:05:22,104
Good job.

131
00:05:30,982 --> 00:05:34,116
Can you tell me what kind
of blinds you got caught in?

132
00:05:34,159 --> 00:05:35,944
- I don't know.

133
00:05:44,518 --> 00:05:47,390
Let's get Iggy and
Child Services down here now.

134
00:05:47,434 --> 00:05:50,132
- What do you think?
- Let's just hope I'm wrong.

135
00:05:54,397 --> 00:05:57,444
- I was, uh, cooking breakfast.

136
00:05:57,487 --> 00:06:00,969
Calvin was in his room playing,
and it was quiet.

137
00:06:01,012 --> 00:06:03,667
It's never quiet,
so I went to check in on him

138
00:06:03,711 --> 00:06:07,845
and I saw a cord, uh,

139
00:06:07,889 --> 00:06:09,412
wrapped around his little neck.

140
00:06:09,456 --> 00:06:12,415
And I tried to rip it off,

141
00:06:12,459 --> 00:06:13,721
but it was all knotted up,

142
00:06:13,764 --> 00:06:16,854
so I started screaming
for Alana.

143
00:06:16,898 --> 00:06:18,987
- I turned the house
upside down

144
00:06:19,030 --> 00:06:20,510
trying to find scissors.

145
00:06:20,554 --> 00:06:24,384
By the time I got them,
Calvin was turning blue.

146
00:06:24,427 --> 00:06:27,691
He was thrashing,
so Ethan had to hold him still.

147
00:06:27,735 --> 00:06:31,086
You know, I--I was
scared I was gonna cut him.

148
00:06:31,129 --> 00:06:34,916
But I got them off
and we called 911.

149
00:06:36,918 --> 00:06:38,833
- Now, if the police were
to come to your home--

150
00:06:38,876 --> 00:06:41,009
- The police?
- Yeah, the police.

151
00:06:41,052 --> 00:06:42,140
If they were to come
to your home, they would see

152
00:06:42,184 --> 00:06:43,794
a piece of cord
lying on the floor

153
00:06:43,838 --> 00:06:46,188
where your wife cut it, right?

154
00:06:46,231 --> 00:06:49,713
- You know,
I think I threw it away.

155
00:06:49,757 --> 00:06:50,888
- You threw it away?

156
00:06:50,932 --> 00:06:53,587
- Yes, after we got him loose.

157
00:06:53,630 --> 00:06:55,153
- But the rest of the cord

158
00:06:55,197 --> 00:06:58,069
would still be dangling there,
severed.

159
00:06:58,113 --> 00:06:59,723
That's what the police
would see.

160
00:07:02,683 --> 00:07:03,727
- And--and they would also see

161
00:07:03,771 --> 00:07:05,163
the scissors
lying on the floor.

162
00:07:05,207 --> 00:07:06,730
And the drawers that
Alana looked through,

163
00:07:06,774 --> 00:07:08,428
they would all be open.

164
00:07:08,471 --> 00:07:09,907
And the breakfast
that you were cooking

165
00:07:09,951 --> 00:07:12,040
would still be...

166
00:07:12,083 --> 00:07:14,216
on the stove.

167
00:07:14,259 --> 00:07:16,784
- Th-there were no scissors.

168
00:07:16,827 --> 00:07:19,613
Um, there was no cord.

169
00:07:21,179 --> 00:07:23,486
It was, uh...

170
00:07:26,620 --> 00:07:28,099
Just me.

171
00:07:28,143 --> 00:07:29,753
But I swear,
it'll never happen again.

172
00:07:29,797 --> 00:07:32,103
Please don't--
please don't take him away.

173
00:07:32,147 --> 00:07:36,891
- So what are you saying,
that I'm lying?

174
00:07:36,934 --> 00:07:40,460
- The marks on Calvin's neck
aren't abrasions.

175
00:07:40,503 --> 00:07:42,592
They're bruises.

176
00:07:42,636 --> 00:07:45,465
A cord didn't do it.
Hands did.

177
00:07:51,296 --> 00:07:53,516
It was me.

178
00:07:53,560 --> 00:07:55,866
He was having a tantrum.

179
00:07:55,910 --> 00:07:57,520
I just snapped.

180
00:07:57,564 --> 00:08:00,958
I didn't know I was choking him.
I just wanted him to stop.

181
00:08:01,002 --> 00:08:03,091
- Ethan, I don't think
that your son

182
00:08:03,134 --> 00:08:06,921
was choked by a man.

183
00:08:06,964 --> 00:08:09,532
The wounds on his neck
were far too small.

184
00:08:09,576 --> 00:08:12,187
- May I see your hands?

185
00:08:16,191 --> 00:08:18,019
- A person who chokes someone

186
00:08:18,062 --> 00:08:21,065
often has defensive wounds
on their hands

187
00:08:21,109 --> 00:08:23,807
from the fingernails
of the person they're choking.

188
00:08:23,851 --> 00:08:25,069
You don't.

189
00:08:33,295 --> 00:08:35,036
- What happened
to your brother, Juliet?

190
00:08:38,082 --> 00:08:40,998
- I wanted his phone,

191
00:08:41,042 --> 00:08:43,261
so I took it.

192
00:08:45,655 --> 00:08:48,484
- Thank you for choosing
Barcroft insurance.

193
00:08:48,528 --> 00:08:49,616
This is Jonathan, how can I
be of service to you today?

194
00:08:49,659 --> 00:08:50,834
- Uh, Jonathan, hi.

195
00:08:50,878 --> 00:08:53,533
This is, uh, Dr. Max Goodwin,

196
00:08:53,576 --> 00:08:56,187
uh, calling about
a recent policy change.

197
00:08:56,231 --> 00:08:58,886
No, no, I don't need billing.
Operator.

198
00:08:58,929 --> 00:09:01,410
- I'm sorry.
I didn't catch that.

199
00:09:01,453 --> 00:09:02,803
- Operator!

200
00:09:02,846 --> 00:09:05,545
- This is regarding
account number 42118?

201
00:09:05,588 --> 00:09:07,068
- No, it's regarding Paz Aquino.

202
00:09:07,111 --> 00:09:09,461
She's not a number.
She's a person.

203
00:09:09,505 --> 00:09:11,594
I know this is
the wrong department, Frank,

204
00:09:11,638 --> 00:09:13,509
but it seems to be
the only department

205
00:09:13,553 --> 00:09:15,903
populated by people.

206
00:09:15,946 --> 00:09:17,165
- Our call center's
in Bangalore.

207
00:09:17,208 --> 00:09:18,558
- Bangalore, wow.

208
00:09:18,601 --> 00:09:20,690
Uh, is there any way
you could connect me

209
00:09:20,734 --> 00:09:23,084
to someone a little closer
to this side of the Earth?

210
00:09:23,127 --> 00:09:25,869
- Good afternoon.
- Mm, is it?

211
00:09:25,913 --> 00:09:28,524
you don't happen to be located

212
00:09:28,568 --> 00:09:31,527
anywhere in the
Western Hemisphere, do you?

213
00:09:31,571 --> 00:09:33,747
- I'm in Kuala Lumpur.
- Kuala Lumpur.

214
00:09:33,790 --> 00:09:35,139
Um, forgive my ignorance.

215
00:09:35,183 --> 00:09:38,012
Is that closer to New York City
than Bangalore?

216
00:09:38,055 --> 00:09:40,101
- Please hold.
Let me check on that.

217
00:09:40,144 --> 00:09:42,625
Happy to.

218
00:09:44,888 --> 00:09:47,630
- How do you think Calvin felt
when you hurt him?

219
00:09:50,851 --> 00:09:53,941
- Well, you know,
if I had to take a guess--

220
00:09:53,984 --> 00:09:56,683
which I don't,
but I'm going to--

221
00:09:56,726 --> 00:10:00,687
I would say that
he was probably afraid.

222
00:10:00,730 --> 00:10:02,210
- I don't know.

223
00:10:02,253 --> 00:10:04,952
- Hey, I am going
to say a sentence,

224
00:10:04,995 --> 00:10:06,954
and then you tell me
if it describes you.

225
00:10:06,997 --> 00:10:08,520
Can we do that?

226
00:10:08,564 --> 00:10:09,696
Okay, cool.

227
00:10:09,739 --> 00:10:14,526
"I think that
most other people are stupid."

228
00:10:14,570 --> 00:10:16,224
- I don't think that.

229
00:10:16,267 --> 00:10:18,008
- All right,
what about this one.

230
00:10:18,052 --> 00:10:20,184
"I manipulate people
to get what I want."

231
00:10:20,228 --> 00:10:21,969
- No.

232
00:10:24,014 --> 00:10:26,843
- Juliet, come on.

233
00:10:26,887 --> 00:10:28,497
It's okay.
It's just me and you in here.

234
00:10:28,540 --> 00:10:29,759
Right?

235
00:10:29,803 --> 00:10:31,674
I've seen tons of kids
come through here.

236
00:10:31,718 --> 00:10:36,287
It's obvious to me that
you are, like, mega smart.

237
00:10:36,331 --> 00:10:38,550
I'll bet you're the best
at manipulating people.

238
00:10:41,031 --> 00:10:42,293
- I'm really good at it.

239
00:10:42,337 --> 00:10:43,686
- Why?

240
00:10:43,730 --> 00:10:45,601
Why do you think
you're so good at it?

241
00:10:45,645 --> 00:10:49,692
- It's--it's kind of like
when I draw.

242
00:10:49,736 --> 00:10:51,999
- You mean manipulating people
makes you feel in control?

243
00:10:52,042 --> 00:10:53,870
- No.

244
00:10:53,914 --> 00:10:55,916
I mean, it's just really easy.

245
00:11:01,748 --> 00:11:03,619
- Mackenzie Adams?
- Yeah, hi.

246
00:11:03,663 --> 00:11:05,665
- Hi.
- This is my husband, John.

247
00:11:05,708 --> 00:11:06,883
Hi.

248
00:11:06,927 --> 00:11:08,145
- I'm Dr. Reynolds,
cardiothoracic surgery.

249
00:11:08,189 --> 00:11:10,191
- Cardio?

250
00:11:10,234 --> 00:11:12,019
- Uh, we came here because

251
00:11:12,062 --> 00:11:14,674
my wife, uh,
lost control of her bladder.

252
00:11:14,717 --> 00:11:15,979
- I'm sure it's just a UTI.

253
00:11:16,023 --> 00:11:17,546
- Well, no.

254
00:11:17,589 --> 00:11:18,982
The urologist said that all of
your tests came back negative,

255
